## Site Search Implementation Plan

### Overview

This plan adds a command palette-style search (Cmd+K / Ctrl+K) to the Acolyte header that allows users to quickly find and navigate to any tool. It involves five coordinated changes: a centralized tool data index, a new `cmdk`-based shadcn Command UI component, a SiteSearch wrapper component, header integration, and sidebar refactoring.

---

### Step 1: Create the centralized tool index -- `/Users/jbouder/repos/jbouder/acolyte/lib/tools-data.ts`

**Purpose:** Single source of truth for all tool metadata, replacing the hardcoded array in `app-sidebar.tsx` and supporting search with descriptions and keywords.

**Type definition:**

```ts
import { LucideIcon } from 'lucide-react';

export type ToolCategory = 'API Testing' | 'Analysis' | 'Utilities' | 'Other';

export interface Tool {
  title: string;
  url: string;
  icon: LucideIcon;
  description: string;
  category: ToolCategory;
  keywords: string[];
}
```

**Key design decisions:**

- The `icon` field stores the Lucide component reference (e.g., `Code2`), not a string. This keeps the existing pattern where `<item.icon />` is rendered in JSX. Since Lucide icons are plain function components, they are safe to import in both client and server modules -- but in practice this file will only be imported by client components (`app-sidebar.tsx` and `site-search.tsx`), so there is no RSC concern.
- The `category` field groups tools for the command palette display (grouping results under "API Testing", "Analysis", "Utilities"), matching the categories already visible on the home page.
- The `keywords` array provides additional search terms beyond the title. For example, the JSON Formatter tool would include `["json", "format", "prettify", "minify", "validate"]` so that typing "prettify" still surfaces it.
- The `description` is a short one-line string (e.g., "Test REST API endpoints with custom headers and request bodies") used in search result display.

**Full tool data array:** The export `tools` will contain all 20 items currently in `app-sidebar.tsx`, plus descriptions and keywords. The "Home" entry should be excluded from search results since it is not a tool -- it can either be omitted from the array or given a special category. The sidebar will filter/include it separately.

Here is how the data maps out (all 20 sidebar entries):

| Title | URL | Icon | Category | Description (short) |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Home | `/` | `Home` | Other | (excluded from search or handled specially) |
| APIs | `/apis` | `Code2` | API Testing | Test REST API endpoints with custom headers and bodies |
| SSE | `/sse` | `Zap` | API Testing | Connect to Server-Sent Events streams |
| WebSockets | `/websockets` | `Cable` | API Testing | Test WebSocket connections and send messages |
| WebTransport | `/webtransport` | `Wifi` | API Testing | Test WebTransport connections |
| Web Stats | `/web-stats` | `Settings` | Analysis | View browser and device statistics |
| Website Analysis | `/website-analysis` | `BarChart3` | Analysis | Analyze website performance and metrics |
| Accessibility Checker | `/accessibility-checker` | `ScanEye` | Analysis | Check web pages for accessibility issues |
| Dependency Analysis | `/dependency-analysis` | `GitBranch` | Analysis | Analyze npm package dependencies |
| SBOM Report | `/sbom-report` | `PackageSearch` | Analysis | Generate Software Bill of Materials reports |
| Markdown Preview | `/markdown-preview` | `Eye` | Utilities | Preview and render markdown content |
| Mermaid Preview | `/mermaid-preview` | `GitGraph` | Utilities | Preview Mermaid diagrams and flowcharts |
| Swagger Viewer | `/swagger-viewer` | `BookOpen` | Utilities | View and explore OpenAPI/Swagger definitions |
| Base64 Encoding | `/base64` | `FileText` | Utilities | Encode and decode Base64 strings |
| JSON Formatter | `/json-formatter` | `Braces` | Utilities | Format, validate, and minify JSON |
| Regex Tester | `/regex` | `SearchCode` | Utilities | Test regular expressions with live matching |
| Color Picker | `/color-picker` | `Palette` | Utilities | Pick colors and convert between formats |
| JWT Decoder | `/jwt` | `Key` | Utilities | Decode and inspect JSON Web Tokens |
| Notepad | `/notepad` | `StickyNote` | Utilities | Quick notes with persistent storage |
| Games | `/games` | `Gamepad2` | Other | Browser-based games and diversions |

**Exports:**

```ts
// All tools including Home
export const allTools: Tool[] = [ ... ];

// Tools for search (excludes Home)
export const searchableTools: Tool[] = allTools.filter(t => t.url !== '/');

// Tools for sidebar navigation (all items)
export const sidebarTools: Tool[] = allTools;
```

This way, the sidebar imports `sidebarTools` (or just `allTools`) and the search component imports `searchableTools`.

---

### Step 2: Install `cmdk` and add the shadcn Command component

**2a. Install the `cmdk` package**

Run:
```bash
npm install cmdk
```

The `cmdk` package (by Paco) provides a composable, accessible command menu primitive. It is the underlying dependency for shadcn/ui's Command component. The current version is `cmdk@1.x` which works with React 19.

**2b. Create `/Users/jbouder/repos/jbouder/acolyte/components/ui/command.tsx`**

This is the standard shadcn/ui Command component file. It follows the exact pattern from the shadcn docs for new-york style. The file should contain:

- `Command` -- the root, wrapping `CommandPrimitive` from cmdk
- `CommandDialog` -- wraps `Command` inside a `Dialog` (using the existing Radix Dialog from `@/components/ui/dialog`)
- `CommandInput` -- the search input
- `CommandList` -- the scrollable results area
- `CommandEmpty` -- shown when no results match
- `CommandGroup` -- groups results with a heading
- `CommandItem` -- individual result items
- `CommandSeparator` -- visual divider between groups
- `CommandShortcut` -- displays keyboard shortcut hints

The standard shadcn command component code is well-established. Key styling points:
- Uses `cn()` from `@/lib/utils` for class merging (consistent with all other UI components)
- Uses `DialogContent` without the close button (the `CommandDialog` variant customizes the dialog content)
- The component file includes `'use client'` at the top since it uses refs and DOM interactions

Here is the key structural outline:

```tsx
'use client';

import { Command as CommandPrimitive } from 'cmdk';
import { Search } from 'lucide-react';
import * as React from 'react';

import { Dialog, DialogContent, DialogDescription, DialogTitle } from '@/components/ui/dialog';
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils';

const Command = React.forwardRef<...>(({ className, ...props }, ref) => (
  <CommandPrimitive
    ref={ref}
    className={cn('flex h-full w-full flex-col overflow-hidden rounded-md bg-popover text-popover-foreground', className)}
    {...props}
  />
));

function CommandDialog({ children, ...props }: React.ComponentProps<typeof Dialog>) {
  return (
    <Dialog {...props}>
      <DialogContent className="overflow-hidden p-0">
        <DialogTitle className="sr-only">Search tools</DialogTitle>
        <DialogDescription className="sr-only">Search for tools by name or keyword</DialogDescription>
        <Command className="[&_[cmdk-group-heading]]:px-2 [&_[cmdk-group-heading]]:font-medium [&_[cmdk-group-heading]]:text-muted-foreground ...">
          {children}
        </Command>
      </DialogContent>
    </Dialog>
  );
}

// CommandInput, CommandList, CommandEmpty, CommandGroup, CommandItem, CommandSeparator, CommandShortcut
// ... following standard shadcn patterns
```

**Important note on the `DialogContent`:** The existing `dialog.tsx` in this project includes an automatic close button (`<DialogPrimitive.Close>` with `<X>` icon). Inside `CommandDialog`, the standard shadcn approach removes or overrides this. The cleanest solution is to have `CommandDialog` use `DialogPortal` and `DialogOverlay` directly rather than `DialogContent`, so the close button is not rendered. Alternatively, the `DialogContent` could accept an optional prop like `showCloseButton={false}`, but that would require modifying dialog.tsx. The simpler approach: have `CommandDialog` compose the dialog primitives directly, bypassing `DialogContent`, which is the standard shadcn pattern.

---

### Step 3: Create the SiteSearch component -- `/Users/jbouder/repos/jbouder/acolyte/components/site-search.tsx`

**Purpose:** A `'use client'` component that renders a trigger button in the header and opens a command palette dialog.

**Behavior:**

1. **Trigger Button:** A button in the header showing a search icon and the text "Search tools..." with a keyboard shortcut badge (showing the platform-appropriate shortcut). On desktop it shows as a wider button with placeholder text; on small screens it collapses to an icon-only button.

2. **Keyboard Shortcut:** Registers a global `keydown` listener for `Cmd+K` (Mac) / `Ctrl+K` (other platforms) to open/close the dialog. This uses `useEffect` for the event listener.

3. **Dialog Content:** Opens a `CommandDialog` containing:
   - `CommandInput` with placeholder "Type a tool name or keyword..."
   - `CommandList` with `CommandEmpty` showing "No tools found."
   - `CommandGroup` entries for each category ("API Testing", "Analysis", "Utilities", "Other"), each containing `CommandItem` entries for that category's tools
   - Each `CommandItem` renders: `<tool.icon className="mr-2 h-4 w-4" />`, the tool title, and a muted description

4. **Navigation:** When a `CommandItem` is selected (clicked or Enter key), the component:
   - Calls `router.push(tool.url)` using Next.js `useRouter` from `next/navigation`
   - Closes the dialog by setting `open` to `false`

5. **Filtering:** `cmdk` provides built-in filtering. The `CommandItem` `value` prop should be set to a combined string of the tool's title, description, and keywords (e.g., `"APIs Test REST API endpoints rest http request get post put delete"`) so that cmdk's fuzzy search matches across all these terms.

**Key implementation details:**

```tsx
'use client';

import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation';
import { useCallback, useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { Search } from 'lucide-react';

import { Button } from '@/components/ui/button';
import {
  CommandDialog,
  CommandEmpty,
  CommandGroup,
  CommandInput,
  CommandItem,
  CommandList,
} from '@/components/ui/command';
import { searchableTools, type ToolCategory } from '@/lib/tools-data';

export function SiteSearch() {
  const [open, setOpen] = useState(false);
  const router = useRouter();

  // Register Cmd+K / Ctrl+K keyboard shortcut
  useEffect(() => {
    const down = (e: KeyboardEvent) => {
      if (e.key === 'k' && (e.metaKey || e.ctrlKey)) {
        e.preventDefault();
        setOpen((prev) => !prev);
      }
    };
    document.addEventListener('keydown', down);
    return () => document.removeEventListener('keydown', down);
  }, []);

  const handleSelect = useCallback(
    (url: string) => {
      setOpen(false);
      router.push(url);
    },
    [router],
  );

  // Group tools by category
  const categories: ToolCategory[] = ['API Testing', 'Analysis', 'Utilities', 'Other'];
  const grouped = categories
    .map((cat) => ({
      category: cat,
      tools: searchableTools.filter((t) => t.category === cat),
    }))
    .filter((g) => g.tools.length > 0);

  return (
    <>
      <Button
        variant="outline"
        className="relative h-9 w-9 p-0 xl:h-9 xl:w-60 xl:justify-start xl:px-3 xl:py-2"
        onClick={() => setOpen(true)}
      >
        <Search className="h-4 w-4 xl:mr-2" />
        <span className="hidden xl:inline-flex">Search tools...</span>
        <kbd className="pointer-events-none absolute right-1.5 top-[50%] translate-y-[-50%] hidden h-5 select-none items-center gap-1 rounded border bg-muted px-1.5 font-mono text-[10px] font-medium opacity-100 xl:flex">
          <span className="text-xs"></span>K
        </kbd>
      </Button>
      <CommandDialog open={open} onOpenChange={setOpen}>
        <CommandInput placeholder="Type a tool name or keyword..." />
        <CommandList>
          <CommandEmpty>No tools found.</CommandEmpty>
          {grouped.map(({ category, tools }) => (
            <CommandGroup key={category} heading={category}>
              {tools.map((tool) => (
                <CommandItem
                  key={tool.url}
                  value={`${tool.title} ${tool.description} ${tool.keywords.join(' ')}`}
                  onSelect={() => handleSelect(tool.url)}
                >
                  <tool.icon className="mr-2 h-4 w-4" />
                  <div>
                    <span className="font-medium">{tool.title}</span>
                    <span className="ml-2 text-sm text-muted-foreground">
                      {tool.description}
                    </span>
                  </div>
                </CommandItem>
              ))}
            </CommandGroup>
          ))}
        </CommandList>
      </CommandDialog>
    </>
  );
}
```

**Platform-aware shortcut display:** The keyboard shortcut badge in the trigger button shows a Mac command key symbol. For full correctness, a small hook or inline check using `navigator.platform` (or `navigator.userAgentData`) could determine whether to show the Mac symbol or "Ctrl". However, since this is rendered on the client and the symbol is purely cosmetic, a simpler approach is to render after mount using a state variable initialized in `useEffect`. This avoids hydration mismatches.

**Responsive behavior:**
- On screens `xl` and above: The button shows as a wide search bar with "Search tools..." text and the keyboard shortcut badge
- On smaller screens: The button collapses to an icon-only button (just the search magnifying glass)
- This mirrors common patterns (VS Code, GitHub, Vercel dashboard)

---

### Step 4: Integrate into the header -- `/Users/jbouder/repos/jbouder/acolyte/app/layout.tsx`

**Current header (line 64-69 of layout.tsx):**

```tsx
<header className="sticky top-0 flex h-17 shrink-0 items-center gap-2 border-b bg-background px-4">
  <SidebarTrigger className="-ml-1" />
  <div className="ml-auto flex items-center gap-2">
    <GitHubLink />
    <ThemeToggle />
  </div>
</header>
```

**Modified header:**

```tsx
import { SiteSearch } from '@/components/site-search';

// ...

<header className="sticky top-0 flex h-17 shrink-0 items-center gap-2 border-b bg-background px-4">
  <SidebarTrigger className="-ml-1" />
  <div className="ml-auto flex items-center gap-2">
    <SiteSearch />
    <GitHubLink />
    <ThemeToggle />
  </div>
</header>
```

**Server/client component boundary:** The layout.tsx file is a server component. The `SiteSearch` component is a `'use client'` component. This is perfectly fine -- server components can render client components as children. The import and usage of `<SiteSearch />` in the server component layout is the standard Next.js pattern (same as the existing `<GitHubLink />` and `<ThemeToggle />` which are both `'use client'` components already imported and used in this server layout).

No changes to the `z-index` or stacking context are needed because the Dialog from Radix uses `z-50` (matching the existing dialog component) and portals to the body, so it will overlay correctly.

---

### Step 5: Refactor the sidebar -- `/Users/jbouder/repos/jbouder/acolyte/components/app-sidebar.tsx`

**Current state:** The sidebar defines its own `items` array (lines 41-142) with all the Lucide icon imports and `{ title, url, icon }` objects.

**After refactoring:**

```tsx
'use client';

import Image from 'next/image';
import Link from 'next/link';
import { usePathname } from 'next/navigation';

import {
  Sidebar,
  SidebarContent,
  SidebarGroup,
  SidebarGroupContent,
  SidebarHeader,
  SidebarMenu,
  SidebarMenuButton,
  SidebarMenuItem,
} from '@/components/ui/sidebar';
import { allTools } from '@/lib/tools-data';

export function AppSidebar() {
  const pathname = usePathname();

  return (
    <Sidebar>
      <SidebarHeader className="border-b border-sidebar-border h-17">
        {/* ... unchanged logo section ... */}
      </SidebarHeader>
      <SidebarContent>
        <SidebarGroup>
          <SidebarGroupContent>
            <SidebarMenu>
              {allTools.map((item) => (
                <SidebarMenuItem key={item.title}>
                  <SidebarMenuButton asChild isActive={pathname === item.url}>
                    <Link href={item.url}>
                      <item.icon />
                      <span>{item.title}</span>
                    </Link>
                  </SidebarMenuButton>
                </SidebarMenuItem>
              ))}
            </SidebarMenu>
          </SidebarGroupContent>
        </SidebarGroup>
      </SidebarContent>
    </Sidebar>
